text: Two non-divers plunging to 47m, they're already dead. They'd probably survive the ride to the bottom if they can equalise quickly (unlikely because most people would panic), but they'd enjoy significant nitrogen narcosis at that depth.  It's unlikely they'd be coherent enough to communicate effectively let alone make reasonable decisions. With a single tank with no experience, even a small female with small lungs is unlikely to last an hour before her air runs out. If they survive all this, after 10 minutes at the bottom their blood would be saturated with nitrogen.  Depending how long there were down, it could take hours to return to the surface safely. A level headed and experienced diver might have a chance of surviving this event.  Someone on their first trip underwater would have no chance.  The sharks are incidental...

text: OMG...movies like this one are the reason, why people are so afraid of sharks.  I did cage diving in South Africa and it was one of the best experiences in my whole life. We had 3-4 Great Whites at our location. 1 young one with not more than 2 meters, 2 were females, about 3-4 meters long, and one bigger male, 5-6 meters long. They were not aggressive at all, instead they were curious about what strange beings like us are doing in THEIR environment. The only thing that interested them was the chunk of rotten fish on a rope, that was used by the very professional crew of that cage diving ship to guide the sharks closer to the cage.  Now, I recommend everyone to do at least one cage dive in his/her life. You will see, that sharks are beautiful animals. You have to look at them as the lions or leopards of the sea. Yes, they are predators and yes they CAN be dangerous. But only under very specific circumstances (i.e. if they mistake a swimmer or surfer with diving suite as one of their prey: seals and sea lions). Honestly, you also wouldn't just walk at a group of lions and try to touch them, wouldn't you? Same with sharks: respectfull distance yes, fear no.  Still the most dangerous "animal" on this planet is the human. Compared to only a few dozend shark attacks with deadly ending WORLDWIDE every year, sharks are killed in MILLIONS by humans every year. Mostly just because some dumb pieces of sh** in south-asian countries believe, that dried shark fins work like Viagra. So the fishers catch the shark, cut off his fins without killing the shark and throw back the living shark in the ocean. The shark then suffocates, because he needs to swim to be able to breath.  Same bullsh*t like shark fins counts for rhino horn, tiger bones and what ever else those dumb motherf***ers in southern asian countries, mostly Vietnam, eat or sniff to get an errection!
